[Event "Casual game"]
[Site "New Orleans, LA USA"]
[Date "1848.??.??"]
[White "Paul Morphy"]
[Black "Alonzo Morphy"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C33"]
[Opening "King's Gambit Accepted: Bishop's Gambit, Greco Variation"]
[StudyName "Morphy's Best Games"]
[ChapterName "Paul Morphy - Alonzo Morphy"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/DpHhCQmZ/9LNy23Or"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/CheckRaiseMate"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ This study is designed to let you play "solitaire chess" with the best games of Paul Morphy. You'll play alongside Morphy, trying to guess his moves.

The opening moves are indicated by arrows. Just play those out. After the first few moves, the exercise starts. } { [%cal Ge2e4] }
1. e4 e5 { [%cal Gf2f4] } 2. f4 { The King's Gambit. Modern engines don't love it, but it's an opening with a rich tradition that can still be effective in games between humans. } 2... exf4 { [%cal Gf1c4] } 3. Bc4 Qh4+ { [%cal Ge1f1] } 4. Kf1 { The king is forced to move, but it's (reasonably) safe on f1, and Black will have to lose time retreating the queen at some point. } 4... Bc5 { Start here! You're playing as White alongside Morphy. } 5. d4! { Preventing Black's threat of Qf2# while grabbing space in the center and hitting the bishop. } 5... Bb6 6. Nf3 { Developing while also creating a threat is almost always a good idea. } 6... Qe7 7. Nc3 { The other knight enters the game, while defending e4 and perhaps threatening to jump into d5. } 7... Nf6 8. Qd3 { Defending the pawn on e4. The advance e5, driving away Black's knight, would have been even stronger. } (8. e5 { Also a good move, in fact stronger than what Morphy played. Give him a break, he was only 11. }) 8... c6 9. Bxf4 { Taking a pawn and bringing out the last minor piece. } 9... d5 10. exd5 { No reason not to take. } 10... O-O 11. d6 { An advanced passed pawn can be very dangerous. This move also opens the diagonal for the bishop on c4 and gains a tempo on Black's queen. } (11. Re1 { is also a very good choice. }) 11... Qd8 12. Re1 { Bringing another piece into the game. } 12... Re8 13. Ng5 { Taking advantage of the downside of Black's last move: it weakened the defense of f7. } 13... Rxe1+ 14. Kxe1 Qe8+ 15. Kd2 { Surrounded by White's pieces, the king is safe here. } (15. Kf1 { is not as good because it locks the rook in on h1. }) 15... Be6 16. Re1 { What really set Morphy apart was that he used EVERY piece. The rook joins the party, increasing the pressure on the bishop on e6 and pinning it to the queen. } 16... Nbd7 17. Nxe6 fxe6 18. Rxe6 { Here Black resigned because there is no good defense to the threat of taking the queen, or other discovered checks by moving the rook. } (18. Bxe6+ Kh8 { is not quite as crushing, although of course White is still doing very well. } 19. Bb3 { [%cal Ge1e8] } (19. Bxd7 Qxd7 20. Re7) 19... Qf8) 18... Qf7 (18... Qd8 19. Re8# { [%cal Gc4g8,Ge8g8] } (19. Rxf6+)) 19. Re7 { [%cal Gc4g8] } 1-0


[Event "Paris"]
[Site "Paris FRA"]
[Date "1858.??.??"]
[White "Paul Morphy"]
[Black "Duke Karl / Count Isouard"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C41"]
[Opening "Philidor Defense"]
[StudyName "Morphy's Best Games"]
[ChapterName "Paul Morphy - Duke Karl / Count Isouard"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/DpHhCQmZ/jxrs6bln"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/CheckRaiseMate"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ This is Morphy's most famous game, so if you've already seen it before, you can skip it. But if not, you're in for a treat.

The game was played in an opera house in Paris. Morphy took on a team of two opponents in consultation. } { [%cal Ge2e4] }
1. e4 e5 { [%cal Gg1f3] } 2. Nf3 d6 { [%cal Gd2d4] } 3. d4 Bg4 { Start here! } 4. dxe5 Bxf3 { How could you have a won a pawn if Black played dxe5? } 5. Qxf3 dxe5 6. Bc4 { Developing a piece and threatening mate. } 6... Nf6 7. Qb3 { "Never move a piece twice in the opening, unless there's a tactic." Here the tactic is a double attack on f7 and b7. The absence of Black's light-squared bishop makes this hard to deal with. } 7... Qe7 8. Nc3 { Morphy prioritizes development over grabbing a pawn. } (8. Qxb7 { Grabbing the pawn would allow Black to force a queen trade with Qb4+. Being up a pawn in the endgame is also a good outcome, so this move is not bad at all, but apparently Morphy wanted to finish things in the middlegame. } 8... Qb4+ 9. Qxb4 Bxb4+ 10. c3) (8. Bxf7+ { Another good option. If Black takes, they will no longer have the resource of Qb4+. } 8... Qxf7 9. Qxb7 { [%csl Ra8][%cal Gb7a8] }) 8... c6 9. Bg5 { Pinning the knight. } 9... b5 10. Nxb5! { Very important move! If you wanted to retreat the bishop, pay special attention to this one. You have a huge lead in development! Why should your opponent get to push you around? } 10... cxb5 11. Bxb5+ Nbd7 12. O-O-O! { The most efficient way to get the rooks into the game. } (12. Rd1 { Not as good as 0-0-0 because the h1 rook cannot now go to the d-file. }) 12... Rd8 13. Rxd7! { Keeping the momentum going. } (13. Rd3 { Not as stylish as Morphy's move, but equally effective. }) 13... Rxd7 14. Rd1 { All pieces in the game! } 14... Qe6 15. Bxd7+ { Normally you would not want to let your opponent out of a pin like this, but Morphy has already seen a game-ending combination. } 15... Nxd7 16. Qb8+! { Bam! } 16... Nxb8 17. Rd8# { And it's mate on the board. One of the great chess games of all time. } 1-0


[Event "Paul Morphy's best games (annotated): Napoleon Marache vs Paul Morphy"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/study/VQEFoO70/lRsW6c8F"]
[Date "1857"]
[White "Napoleon Marache"]
[Black "Paul Morphy"]
[Result "0-1"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/WannabeRomantic"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C52"]
[Opening "Italian Game: Evans Gambit, Pierce Defense"]
[StudyName "Morphy's Best Games"]
[ChapterName "Napoleon Marache - Paul Morphy"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/DpHhCQmZ/4veAZavA"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

1. e4 { In this game Morphy had Black. Play out the opening moves. } { [%cal Ge7e5] } 1... e5 2. Nf3 { [%cal Gb8c6] } 2... Nc6 3. Bc4 { [%cal Gf8c5] } 3... Bc5 4. b4 { The Evans Gambit. In exchange for the pawn, White gains time to expand in the center. Not a bad opening at all, even today! } { [%cal Gc5b4] } 4... Bxb4 5. c3 { [%cal Gb4a5] } 5... Ba5 6. d4 { [%cal Ge5d4] } 6... exd4 7. e5 { Start here! } 7... d5! { Fighting back in the center and preparing to develop the bishop. } 8. exd6 Qxd6 9. O-O Nge7 { Developing a knight and preparing to castle, while blocking a potential check on the e-file. } 10. Ng5 O-O { Castling and defending f7 at the same time. } 11. Bd3 Bf5 { Once again answering White's threat with a developing move. } 12. Bxf5 Nxf5 13. Ba3 Qg6 { White wins an exchange, but in the meantime Morphy has developed all his pieces and grabbed some pawns. } 14. Bxf8 Qxg5 { The right piece to take. The knight was one of the White king's only defenders, whereas the bishop doesn't have much to do. } 15. Ba3 dxc3 { Development is great, but there's also nothing wrong with grabbing a free pawn. } 16. Bc1 Qg6 17. Bf4 Rd8 { Last piece in the game! Have you noticed how Morphy manages to involve EVERY piece in EVERY game? } 18. Qc2 Ncd4 { The knight jumps into the center of the board while attacking the queen. } 19. Qe4 Ng3!! { A sudden end to the game! Morphy threatens both checkmate and capturing the queen. White can't stop both. } 20. Qxg6 Nde2# 0-1


[Event "1st American chess congress"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/study/VQEFoO70/AMo5AmYg"]
[Date "03 November 1857"]
[Round "4"]
[White "Louis Paulsen"]
[Black "Paul Morphy"]
[Result "0-1"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/WannabeRomantic"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C48"]
[Opening "Four Knights Game: Spanish Variation, Classical Variation"]
[StudyName "Morphy's Best Games"]
[ChapterName "Louis Paulsen - Paul Morphy"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/DpHhCQmZ/LbTkEWzk"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ You're playing as Black alongside Morphy. Play out the opening moves. }
1. e4 { [%cal Ge7e5] } 1... e5 2. Nf3 { [%cal Gb8c6] } 2... Nc6 3. Nc3 { [%cal Gg8f6] } 3... Nf6 4. Bb5 { [%cal Gf8c5] } 4... Bc5 5. O-O { [%cal Ge8g8] } 5... O-O 6. Nxe5 { [%cal Gf8e8] } 6... Re8 { Morphy sacrifices a pawn for quick development. } 7. Nxc6 { [%cal Gd7c6] } 7... dxc6 8. Bc4 { Start here! } 8... b5 { Making the bishop choose a diagonal. } (8... Ng4 { with the idea of Qh4 would in fact have been stronger than Morphy's move. }) (8... Nxe4 { fails to a tactic. } 9. Bxf7+ Kxf7 10. Nxe4 Rxe4 11. Qf3+ { [%cal Gf3f7,Gf3e4] }) 9. Be2 Nxe4 { Now it is safe to take the pawn. } 10. Nxe4 Rxe4 11. Bf3 Re6 { Keeping c6 defended. } 12. c3 Qd3! { A very important move: White can't be allowed to play d4 and take command of the center. } 13. b4 Bb6 (13... Bd6 { also a good option. }) 14. a4 bxa4 { Accepting doubled isolated pawns, but White was threatening to trap the bishop with a5. And if you checkmate your opponent nobody will care about the isolated pawns! } 15. Qxa4 Bd7 (15... Bb7 { would have been stronger, preventing the defensive idea Qa6. }) 16. Ra2 Rae8 { Last piece in the game! } 17. Qa6 Qxf3!! { This queen sacrifice blows White's king position wide open. } 18. gxf3 Rg6+ 19. Kh1 Bh3 { Threatening to set up a checkmate starting with Bg2. } 20. Rd1 Bg2+ 21. Kg1 Bxf3+ 22. Kf1 Bg2+ { Morphy decides to repeat moves. } (22... Rg2 { was the fastest win, planning Rxh2 and Rh1#. }) 23. Kg1 Bh3+ 24. Kh1 Bxf2 { Threatening Bg2#. } 25. Qf1 Bxf1 26. Rxf1 { White has made it into the endgame without getting checkmated, but he's down 2 pawns, and the king isn't out of the woods yet. } 26... Re2 { Rooks on the seventh are usually powerful, and this is no exception. } 27. Ra1 Rh6 { Preparing to break through on h2. } 28. d4 Be3! { Blocking the threat to the rook on h6 while adding another attacker to h2. White resigned in view of the line Bxe3 Rhxh2+ Kg1 Reg2#. } 0-1


