1. d4 d5 (1... Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 { If you want to use the Exchange as your primary weapon vs. the QGD, it's best to play Nc3 here, so if Black plays d5 you can transpose to your repertoire. } (3. Nf3 d5 { This is the problem with starting with Nf3. This is a different variation of the QGD where you've already committed your knight to f3. }) 3... Bb4) 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 (5. e3?! { It's better to get the bishop outside the pawn chain first. } { [%cal Rc1e3] }) 5... Be7 6. e3 O-O 7. Bd3 c6 8. Qc2 { [%cal Gg5f6,Rc2h7] } 8... Nbd7 9. Nge2 { The idea of this setup is to play f3 and e4. } { [%cal Gf2f3,Ge3e4] } 9... Re8 10. O-O Nf8 11. f3 { [%cal Ge3e4] } *


