1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6 6. Qc2 Be7 7. e3 Nbd7 8. Bd3 O-O 9. Nge2 Re8 10. O-O Nf8 11. f3 Ng6 12. Rad1 h6 { This is a relatively
new try. } (12... Be6 { where the following game is
important for the theory: } 13. Kh1 Rc8 14. e4 dxe4 15. fxe4 Ng4 16. Bc1 c5 17. Bb5 Qc7 18. Nf4 cxd4 19. Bxe8 dxc3 20. Bb5 cxb2 21. Qxb2 Nxf4 22. Bxf4 Qc2 23. Qxc2 Rxc2 24. Rd2 Rxd2 25. Bxd2 Bc5 $17 { Gulko-Sturua, Elista 1998. }) (12... Nh5 { but here Black has more problems, for example: } 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. e4 dxe4 15. fxe4 Be6 16. e5 c5 17. d5 Bg4 18. e6 $40 { Yakovich-Ahlander, Stockholm 1999. }) 13. Bxf6 (13. Bxh6 gxh6 14. Bxg6 fxg6 15. Qxg6+ Kh8 16. Nf4 Bf8 17. e4 $13) 13... Bxf6 14. Bxg6 fxg6 15. e4 g5 16. e5 $146 (16. a4 Be6 17. a5 Be7 18. f4 gxf4 19. Nxf4 Bg5 20. Nxe6) 16... Be7 17. f4 gxf4 18. Nxf4 Rf8 19. Ng6 Rxf1+ 20. Rxf1 Be6 21. Ne2 { Here knights are superior to
bishops. Besides, White can choose which bishop to exchange and which to leave
to Black. } 21... Qd7 22. h4 Re8 23. Ng3 Bf7?! (23... Bd8!? { - this bishop might be
needed to protect the d6-square and to attack the d4-pawn. }) 24. Nxe7+ Rxe7 25. Nf5 $16 { [%csl Rd6] } 25... Re6 26. Nd6 Bg6 27. Qc3 Rxd6 { It is unlikely that Black
could put up with such a knight for too long! } 28. exd6 Qxd6 29. Qa3 Qb8 30. Qe7 Qg3 31. Rf3? { Here White missed a clear win. The rest of the game is
less interesting for this pawn formation. } (31. Rf8+ Kh7 32. Qd8! $18 Be4 33. Rh8+ Kg6 34. Qe8+ Kf5 35. Qf7+ Kg4 36. Qxg7+) 31... Qg4 32. Qf8+ Kh7 33. Qf4 Qd7 34. Rg3 Be4 35. Qe5 Qf7 36. h5 Qd7 37. b4 a6 38. a4 Kg8 39. a5 Kh7 40. Kf2 Kg8 41. Qb8+ Kh7 42. Qf8 Bc2 43. Qf4 Be4 44. Qe5 Kg8 45. Ke3 Kh7 46. Ke2 Kg8 47. Qb8+ Kh7 48. Qf8 Bc2 49. Kd2 Be4 50. Kc1 Qc7 51. Rg4 Qd7 52. Rf4 Bxg2 53. Qf5+ Qxf5 54. Rxf5 Kg8 55. Kd2 Bh3 56. Rf4 Be6 57. Ke3 Bf7 58. Rf5 Kf8 59. Re5 Be8 60. Kf4 Bf7 61. Kg4 Be8 62. Kg3 Bf7 63. Kf4 Be8 64. Kf5 Bxh5 65. Ke6 Bg6 66. Re3 Bc2 67. Rf3+ Kg8 68. b5 cxb5 69. Kxd5 b4 70. Kc4 b3 71. Kc3 g5 72. d5 g4 73. Rf4 h5 74. d6 { 1-0 White wins. } 1-0


