1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 4. Nb5 { Avoiding the pin and threatening c7. } { [%csl Rc7][%cal Gb5c7,Gf4c7] } 4... Na6 { Simply developing and defending c7. } { [%cal Ga6c7] } 5. e3 Be7 { There is no rush to kick the knight out. We just develop and castle. } 6. Nf3 O-O 7. Bd3 (7. Be2 c6 8. Nc3 c5 9. O-O Bd7 10. Ne5 Be8 { [%cal Ga6b4,Gb4c6] }) (7. h4 c6 8. Nc3 c5 9. Ne5 Nb4 10. h5 h6 11. g4 Nd7 { [%cal Gb4c6,Ge7g5] }) (7. Ne5 c5 { Here it's a little more precise to play c5 in one move. } (7... c6?! 8. Nc3 c5 9. Bxa6 bxa6 10. Nc6 { is slightly annoying. }) 8. c3 Nb8 { [%cal Gb8c6] }) 7... c6 8. Nc3 c5 9. Bxa6 { Don't be scared of the doubled pawns. } (9. dxc5 Nxc5 { [%cal Gc5d3] }) (9. O-O c4 10. Be2 Bd7 { [%cal Gb7b4] }) 9... bxa6 { In exchange for doubled pawns, Black has the bishop pair and the open b-file to work with. } 10. O-O Nh5! { Going after the other bishop. } { [%csl Rf4][%cal Gh5f4] } 11. Be5 f6 12. Bg3 Nxg3 13. hxg3 Rb8 { Black stands slightly better thanks to the bishop pair and a flexible pawn structure. } { [%csl Rb2][%cal Gb8b2,Gc8d7] } *


