1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 (2. Nf3 { You can also start with this move. There are some tradeoffs both ways. There's some truth to the "knights before bishops" rule, and after 2. Nf3, a move like 2... c5 (for example) is riskier for Black. But there are also some lines where we benefit from delaying the knight's development. } 2... Nf6 3. c3!? { This is actually a really interesting move order. }) 2... Nf6 (2... c5 3. e3 (3. e4!? { This pawn sacrifice might catch some players off guard. })) 3. e3 c5 (3... e6 4. Nf3 Bd6 (4... c5) 5. Bg3 { Historically this has been played the most often, but probably isn't the way to go, because Black has a plan to force through the e5 break. } (5. Nbd2 { White invites the pawn structure after Bxf4 exf4. In fact, this seems to be pretty good for White, so Black usually ignores it and keeps developing. } 5... O-O 6. Bd3 c5 7. c3 Bxf4 8. exf4 cxd4 9. Nxd4 Qc7 10. Ne2 (10. g3 e5) 10... b6 { [%cal Gc8a6] }) (5. Ne5 { This is the most combative option. White prevents the trade of bishops and installs a knight on e5. }) 5... O-O 6. Nbd2 c5 7. c3 Qc7 8. Bd3 (8. dxc5!? { White should probably try something like this. }) 8... Nbd7 { Black is going to equalize with e5. } { [%cal Ge6e5] } (8... Nc6?! 9. dxc5 { [%cal Gg3c7] }) 9. O-O Bxg3 10. hxg3 e5 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Qxe5 { Black obviously has no problems in this position. }) 4. c3 (4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 { This is the other way to avoid the "bad" version that would occur after c3 here. In this case, White is planning a pawn sacrifice. } (5. c3 { This is what we're trying to avoid (see the mainline). }) 5... Qb6 6. dxc5!? { This is the idea. White ignores the threat to the pawn and focuses on active play. } 6... Qxb2 (6... Qxc5 7. a3 { [%cal Gb2b4,Gc2c4] }) 7. Rb1 Qc3 (7... Qxa2? { is really dangerous. }) 8. Bb5 e6 (8... g6 9. e4!? { From here the play becomes insanely sharp. }) 9. O-O Be7 (9... Bxc5? { I remember this is bad, but why? }) 10. e4!? O-O (10... dxe4?? 11. Nc4!! { The queen can't escape. } { [%csl Rc3] } 11... exf3 12. Rb3! $18) 11. e5 Nd7 12. Nb3 Qb4 13. Nbd4 Qxc5 { White has long-term compensation for the pawn in the form of more space and attacking chances on the kingside. }) (4. dxc5!? { is worth looking as as a curveball. }) 4... Nc6 5. Nd2 { One of the big reasons to start with 2. Bf4 is to be able to play Nd2 here, because this makes Qb6 much less effective. } (5. Nf3 { This is the position we're trying to avoid. } 5... Qb6 6. Qb3 (6. Qc2!? { If you get to this position, this is probably the way to go. Black may mistakenly believe they're in the Qb3 line and fall into a trap. But it's kind of a one trick pony. As long as Black avoids Bf4, they're fine. } 6... Bf5?! (6... g6 { [%cal Gc8f5] }) (6... Nh5!?) 7. dxc5! Bxc2 8. cxb6 axb6 9. Na3 { This is dangerous for Black. } { [%cal Ga3c2,Ga3b5] }) 6... c4 7. Qc2 Bf5 8. Qc1 { White wasted a lot of time moving the queen around, while Black played natural developing moves. If anyone is better, it's Black. } (8. Qxf5 Qxb2 { wins the rook in the corner. } { [%csl Ra1][%cal Gb2a1] })) 5... Bf5 (5... Qb6 6. Qb3 c4 7. Qc2 Bf5? 8. Qxf5 Qxb2 9. Qb1 { Black is just down a piece. }) 6. Ngf3 (6. Qb3 { [%cal Gb3b7] } 6... Qd7 (6... Qc8) 7. Ngf3 c4 (7... e6?! 8. Bb5 { With Ne5 next, the pin is annoying to deal with. } { [%cal Gf3e5] }) 8. Qd1 e6 9. Be2 { This is a typical London structure. } (9. Nh4!? { White could try to imbalance the position by grabbing the bishop. })) 6... Qb6 { Here the standard response Qb3 is not really satisfactory, so White has to get creative. } (6... e6) 7. Nh4 (7. Qb3?! c4 8. Qxb6 axb6 $15 { [%cal Ga8a2,Gb6b4] }) (7. dxc5!? Qxb2 (7... Qxc5 8. Qb3 { It's surprisingly awkward to defend b7. } { [%csl Rb7][%cal Gb3b7] }) 8. Nd4 { Now there are some forced lines where both sides have to know what they're doing. } { [%cal Gd4f5] }) 7... Bd7 8. Qb3 c4 (8... Qxb3 9. axb3 Nh5 { is also fine for Black. }) 9. Qc2 { The point of Nh4 was to enable this retreat. } 9... Nh5 10. Bg3 Nxg3 11. hxg3 $10 { Black has the bishop pair, but White is very solid. } *


