[Event "Casual Classical game"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/mqSeogh8"]
[Date "2024.01.16"]
[White "Squire_Western"]
[Black "Zaxman"]
[Result "1-0"]
[WhiteElo "1822"]
[BlackElo "1713"]
[TimeControl "1800+20"]
[Termination "Normal"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Squire_Western"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "D08"]
[Opening "Queen's Gambit Declined: Albin Countergambit, Normal Line"]
[StudyName "Training**"]
[ChapterName "Squire_Western - Zaxman"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/XaAaEDEu/rsdhwFFv"]

{ A second match in as many weeks with Ev. I imagine he sat down to this game, hands still shaking with anger at the previous loss, eyes glowing with the desire for revenge. Somehow he was able to restore his calm and amiable demeanour by our post game analysis, but Im convinced thats how it happened! :D }
1. d4 { [%clk 0:30:00] } 1... d5 { [%clk 0:30:00] } 2. c4 { [%clk 0:30:11] } 2... e5 { Ive had decent success against c4 with the Albin Countergambit. It seems to be relatively underplayed? } { [%clk 0:30:07] } 3. dxe5 { [%clk 0:30:07] } 3... d4 { [%clk 0:30:20] } 4. Nf3 { [%clk 0:30:17] } 4... Nc6 { [%clk 0:30:34] } 5. a3 { [%clk 0:30:13] } 5... Nge7 { [%clk 0:30:38] } 6. b4 { [%clk 0:30:23] } 6... Ng6 { [%clk 0:30:37] } 7. Bb2 { [%clk 0:30:15] } 7... a5 { [%clk 0:30:39] } 8. b5 { [%clk 0:26:37] } 8... Ncxe5 { [%clk 0:30:44] } 9. Nxe5 { [%clk 0:25:27] } (9. Qxd4 Nxf3+ (9... Qxd4 10. Bxd4 Nxc4 11. e3 Nd6) 10. gxf3) 9... Nxe5 { Playing into the main line e3 coming. } { [%clk 0:30:48] } 10. e3 { [%clk 0:23:36] } 10... Bc5 { Give up a fork for a brutal attack (I hope!) } { [%clk 0:30:07] } 11. exd4 { [%clk 0:22:21] } 11... Bg4 { At this point, I am getting a case of deja vue as I have hefty prep on the board and a time advantage. Could this game go the same way as the first? Its a dangerous looking position, but far from decided yet. } { [%clk 0:29:58] } 12. Be2 { I was hoping for f3, which gives a massive advantage to Black, but my opponent is allergic to it apparently. Im out of prep with Be2. } { [%clk 0:19:50] } (12. f3 Qh4+ 13. g3 Nxf3+ 14. Qxf3 Qe7+) 12... Bxe2 { [%clk 0:28:44] } (12... Nxc4 13. Bc3 Qe7 14. dxc5 Rd8 15. Nd2 Rd3) 13. Kxe2 { This caught me by surprise. I thought the d4 pawn was mine. } { [%clk 0:17:27] } (13. Qxe2 Bxd4 14. O-O (14. Bxd4 Qxd4) 14... Bxb2 15. Qxb2 Nxc4 16. Qe2+ { [%csl Ge8][%cal Ge2c4,Ge2e8] }) 13... Nxc4 { The last two moves were easy to make. Engine? } { [%clk 0:24:27] } (13... Qh4 14. Re1 (14. g3 Qe4+ { [%cal Ge4e2,Ge4h1] }) (14. dxc5 Qg4+ 15. Ke1 Qxg2) 14... O-O-O { The engine like Qh4 and long castle. Creates a tactical advantage on d4. Nice! }) 14. dxc5 { [%clk 0:16:58] } 14... Qe7+ { I didnt see any advantage in trading just yet. With castling possibilities and my rook ready to claim the d file, I'll give a check first. } { [%clk 0:23:31] } 15. Kf1 { [%clk 0:17:05] } 15... Nxb2 { Rd8 would've allowed the queen to cover b2, so I had to jump in with the knight. } { [%clk 0:22:56] } 16. Qe2 { My opponent forces the queens off. I'd like to get a full understanding of why that was advantageous for him. The attack was too potent to allow the queen to continue? } { [%clk 0:16:54] } 16... Qxe2+ { [%clk 0:22:22] } 17. Kxe2 { [%clk 0:17:12] } 17... O-O-O { Castle long to bring my king closer to the queenside pawns for some activity. Nice to land a rook on the open file too.
The engine currently evaluates the position as a piece up for black. How did it go wrong from here? } { [%clk 0:21:12] } 18. Ra2 { [%clk 0:11:58] } 18... Nc4 { I rejected Na4 as I incorrectly calculated it could be trapped. Not the only calculation that will cost me. Rhd8+ would also have been better. The positional advantage is almost gone. } { [%clk 0:19:07] } (18... Rhe8+ 19. Kf3 Rd3+ 20. Kf4 Nc4 (20... Rb3) 21. Rc1) (18... Na4 19. Rc2 { [%csl Gc1][%cal Gh1c1] }) 19. Rc1 { [%clk 0:10:26] } 19... Rhe8+ { [%clk 0:18:40] } 20. Kf1 { The engine say -1.5 and the position looks great for black. Well up on the clock too. What could go wrong from here? } { [%clk 0:10:25] } (20. Kf3 Rd3+) 20... Re5 { The knight isnt hanging due to the back rank threat, so I decided to try and get an attack going. The best I could find was to attack the advanced pawns. However, I failed to notice I had taken away my knights escape squares if and when an extra attcker was applied. } { [%clk 0:17:32] } (20... Ne5) (20... Rd5 21. Rac2 Ne5) 21. Rac2 { The knight is now hanging (or is it?). My opponents relentless strong moves have gradually overwhelmed my strong start. } { [%clk 0:07:59] } 21... Nxa3 { Thinking I had blundered the piece, I grabbed a pawn and hoped that I may grab another in the next few moves. Then who knows, maybe I can pull back the advantage? } { [%clk 0:10:54] } (21... Rxc5 22. Rxc4 (22. a4 Rd4 23. Na3 Nxa3 24. Rxc5 { [%csl Gd7][%cal Gd4d7] }) 22... Rxc4 (22... Rd1+ 23. Rxd1 Rxc4) 23. Rxc4 Rd1+ { A lovely tactical sequence that equalizes. Why didnt I see this? Initially, I thought I would have done well to spot it. But I now think it was a bad miss to not calculate/visualize this sequence. Its clearly the most obvious line and I only had to go three-ply deep to see it. I have been doing a lot of work on making clear two-ply calculations in a position (instead of feeling my way forward move by move). Looks like three-ply calculation training needs to be hurried along! } { [%csl Gb1,Gf1][%cal Gd1b1,Gd1f1] } 24. Ke2 Rxb1 25. a4) 22. Nxa3 { [%clk 0:08:01] } 22... Rd3 { [%clk 0:08:43] } 23. Nc4 { [%clk 0:07:02] } 23... Red5 { And there was my pawn on c5 but I didnt take it as I was loathe to exchange rooks. The end is near if Im not going to engage the rooks! } { [%clk 0:06:50] } 24. Nxa5 { Down a piece. Cannon aimed at my king. The position feels crushing. The engine gives it a full rook up. Im not going anywhere against a strong player.
A good game, with an excellent opportunity for me to capitalize on a strong sharp position. Ev mustve been slightly worried at one point that this game was going the same way as the first! Alas, there's only so long I can remain mistake free. Blunders seem so silly after the fact!
Even before analysis, Ev showed me the missed tactic. His calculation is far better than mine and so it played out. An instructive loss with a clear weakness to work on. Thanks for the late night game and analysis Ev! } { 1-0 Black resigns. } { [%clk 0:06:20] } 1-0


