1. e4 { If you don't see my comments below, press 'z' key to enable engine. } 1... c5 2. Nc3 e6 3. f4 d5 4. e5 Nc6 5. Bb5 Bd7 6. Nf3 Nge7 7. d3 a6 8. Bxc6 Nxc6 9. O-O Be7 10. f5 d4 (10... f6 { Was tempting for a moment but I think the resulting position is better for white than the game. } 11. exf6 Bxf6 12. fxe6 Bxe6 13. Qe2 Qd7) (10... exf5 11. Nxd5 { Was white's idea; I think this is also better for white. }) 11. fxe6 Bxe6 12. Ne4 Qd5 { I'm more interested in winning a tempo here for O-O-O than actually winning this pawn. } { [%cal Rd5e5,Rc6e5] } (12... O-O { Seemed too risky during the game, but looks like the best move to me now. All of white's pieces are poised to attack on the kingside. I calculated some scary looking stuff, but missed some of my alternatives; specifically I don't need to capture a knight on g5. I think now that going for O-O-O was a strategic mistake that made this game too difficult. } 13. Nfg5 (13. Neg5 { Preserves e5 but is less dangerous, because there is no open line for the queen. } 13... Qd7 { Again, I don't think I should take. }) 13... Nxe5 (13... Bxg5?! 14. Nxg5 (14. Bxg5 Qc7 15. Qh5 (15. Nxc5 Nxe5 16. Nxe6 fxe6 17. Qh5 { Maybe this is not so bad. })) 14... Nxe5?? (14... g6 15. Nxe6 fxe6 16. Bh6 Rxf1+ 17. Qxf1 Qh4 (17... Qe7) (17... Nxe5 18. Re1 Ng4 19. Qf4)) 15. Qh5 g6 16. Nxe6 fxe6 17. Qxe5) 14. Qh5 { This is the line that had me worried, but I think it can be defended. } (14. Nxe6 fxe6 { [%csl Ge7][%cal Ge7c5] }) 14... h6 15. Nf3 Nxf3+ (15... Ng6 16. Bxh6 gxh6 17. Qxh6 Bd5) 16. Rxf3 Bd5 17. Bxh6 Bxe4 18. dxe4 gxh6 19. Qxh6 Bg5 20. Rg3 f6 21. Rf1 Qe7 22. Qh5 Qh7 { I don't think white has enough for the piece. } 23. Qxh7+ Kxh7 24. e5 Be3+ 25. Kh1 fxe5) 13. Bf4 h6 { Unnecessary, I'm quite sure. I wanted to stop Ng5 and prepare a pawn storm on the kingside. } (13... O-O-O 14. Neg5) 14. Qd2 g5 15. Bg3 O-O-O 16. Nf6 { Totally missed that this was possible. } 16... Bxf6 17. exf6 Rhe8 18. Qf2 h5 19. h4 gxh4 20. Nxh4 Ne5 21. Nf5 Ng6 { [%cal Rg6e7] } 22. Ne7+ { He does it anyway! And it almost works. } 22... Nxe7 23. fxe7 Rxe7 24. Bh4 f6 25. Qxf6 (25. Bxf6? Rf7) 25... Ree8 (25... Rf7?? { was briefly tempting } 26. Qxd8+ Qxd8 27. Bxd8 Kxd8 28. Rxf7 Bxf7) 26. Rae1 Rd6 27. Bg3 Rg8 28. Re5 Qc6 29. Rg5 Rxg5 (29... Bxa2?? 30. Qxd6 (30. Rxg8+ Bxg8 31. Qxd6) 30... Rxg5 31. Qb8+ Kd7) 30. Qxg5 Rd8 31. Qe7 b6 32. Rf6 Re8 { POSITION } 33. Rf8 Rxf8 (33... Bd7 { Here, I saw dire threats on b8. } 34. Qe5 { I don't see a defense. } { [%cal Rg3b8,Re5b8] } 34... Qb7 35. Rxe8+ Bxe8 36. Qxe8#) 34. Qxf8+ Kb7 { I've spent a lot of time trying to figure out why this happened, but basically it is my old enemy insta-move - I think its the only time it happened this tournament but unfortunately it was decisive. Chess fatigue was a factor - I'd burned a lot of cycles defending this position and this was the second round of the day. I'd earlier played b6 partly to give myself this escape square - especially when rooks were still on this seemed prudent. I'd seen mate on b8 was possible earlier. } (34... Kd7 { I didn't talk to my opponent until about 10 minutes after the game, and I still had not realized my mistake. While I was surprised by Qb8#, afterward I thought the position was indefensible. He pointed out that he doesn't have anything, maybe just the pawn after Kd7. } 35. Qg7+ { I thought this didn't work because I can't block the check. But, there is no enemy rook on the 8th rank; so I can just go back there. } 35... Ke8 36. Qg6+ Ke7 37. Qxh5 { I like black's chances to hold here. Opposite colored bishops and the promotion square will be controlled by my bishop. }) 35. Qb8# { 1-0 White wins. } 1-0


