1. Nf3 { This was an arranged game -- I am studying Check RaiseMate (CRM)'s 1.Nf3 Chessable course and asked if I could try it out against him. } { [%clk 0:30:00] } 1... d5 { [%clk 0:30:00] } 2. g3 { [%clk 0:30:17] } 2... Nf6 { [%clk 0:30:19] } 3. Bg2 { [%clk 0:30:31] } 3... c6 { [%clk 0:30:38] } 4. O-O { [%clk 0:30:44] } 4... Bg4 { [%clk 0:30:55] } 5. h3 { [%clk 0:30:55] } 5... Bxf3 { Not covered in his opening course! I'm on my own. } { [%clk 0:31:13] } 6. Bxf3 { [%clk 0:31:13] } 6... Nbd7 { [%clk 0:31:32] } 7. d4 { Not wanting to allow an uncontested e5. } { [%clk 0:31:22] } 7... e5 { [%clk 0:31:39] } 8. c4 { [%clk 0:30:49] } 8... dxc4 { [%clk 0:29:18] } 9. Nc3 { [%clk 0:29:52] } (9. Nd2 { This was the move expected by CRM and by the computer to quickly recover my pawn. I failed to consider it. } { [%cal Gd2c4] } 9... exd4 10. Nxc4 Bc5 (10... b5 11. Nd2 Ne5) 11. b4) 9... exd4 { [%clk 0:27:16] } (9... Bb4 10. d5 cxd5 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. Qxd5 { [%cal Gf3b7,Gd5c4] }) 10. Qxd4 { [%clk 0:29:54] } 10... Bc5 { [%clk 0:27:35] } 11. Qxc4 { [%clk 0:28:48] } 11... O-O { [%clk 0:27:51] } 12. b4 { I was nervous about Qb3 so this move pushed the dark squared bishop back and also allowed by to dring my bishop to b2 and the long diagonal. Na4 would have been a good response to Qb3 had I played Rd1 instead, for instance. } { [%clk 0:27:09] } (12. Rd1 Qb6 13. Na4 Bxf2+ 14. Kg2) 12... Bb6 { [%clk 0:27:36] } 13. Bg2 { Stepping back from a Ne5 fork. There are other options: } { [%clk 0:25:03] } (13. Bb2 Ne5 14. Qb3 Nxf3+ 15. exf3 Qd7) (13. Rd1 Ne5 14. Qb3 Nxf3+ 15. exf3 Qe7) 13... Qe7 { [%clk 0:26:18] } 14. e3 { [%clk 0:23:41] } (14. b5 Ne5 15. Qb3 { [%cal Gc1a3,Ga3f8] } 15... Rfe8 16. bxc6 bxc6 17. Na4) 14... Ne5 { [%clk 0:26:11] } 15. Qb3 { [%clk 0:23:12] } 15... Rfe8 { Stepping out of any problems that might result from a future Ba3. } { [%clk 0:21:46] } (15... Nd3 16. b5 { I didn't see this response during the game but it's important to leave the dark squared Bishop on c1 to protect e3. } (16. Ba3 Nxf2 17. Rxf2 (17. b5 Qxe3) 17... Qxe3 18. Nd1 Qxb3 19. axb3 Bxf2+ 20. Nxf2) 16... Qe5) 16. Rd1 { Preventing Nd3 } { [%clk 0:22:51] } 16... h5 { [%clk 0:21:42] } 17. Bb2 { [%clk 0:20:03] } 17... h4 { [%clk 0:21:47] } 18. g4 { CRM was tempted to initiate an attack with a piece sacrifice on g4 or e3. My knight and Queen are not well placed to aid in my King's defense. } { [%clk 0:18:58] } 18... Rad8 { [%clk 0:19:31] } (18... Nexg4 19. hxg4 Bxe3 20. fxe3 (20. Re1 Bxf2+ 21. Kxf2 Nxg4+ 22. Kg1 Qd6 23. Ne4) 20... Qxe3+ 21. Kh1 h3) (18... Bxe3 19. fxe3 Nexg4) 19. Ne2 { I was feeling good at this point -- my knight and queen are better able to cover the kingside, my dark square bishop is on a great long diagonal, my rooks are connected, and my knight can jump into d4 to assert influence in the center. } { [%clk 0:18:27] } 19... a6 { I didn't understand this move during the game -- CRM was protecting against b5 and a minority attack, but sadly
that hadn't crossed my mind. } { [%clk 0:17:46] } 20. Nd4 { [%clk 0:17:31] } 20... g6 { Nf5 was too big a threat to allow even if it meant opening up the long diagonal to my dark squared bishop and possibly my queen also. Forcing this concession from CRM is basically the highlight of my chess career. :) } { [%clk 0:14:47] } (20... Nfd7 21. Nf5 Qg5) 21. Nf3 { [%clk 0:14:37] } (21. Qc3 Nd5 22. Bxd5 Rxd5 23. f4 Bxd4 24. Rxd4 Nf3+ { [%cal Gf3d4] }) 21... Nfd7 { [%clk 0:10:40] } (21... Bc7 22. Nxh4 Nfxg4 23. Nxg6 Nxg6 24. hxg4 Qh4 25. Qc4 Qh2+ 26. Kf1 Nh4) 22. Nxh4?? { And that's the ball game, folks. Fun while it lasted. } { [%clk 0:12:54] } (22. Qc3 Bc7 { [%cal Gb2h8] }) (22. Nxe5 Nxe5 23. Qc3 g5) 22... Qxh4 { [%clk 0:10:28] } 23. Qc3 { [%clk 0:11:38] } 23... f6 { [%clk 0:10:34] } 24. Rd6 { [%clk 0:08:18] } 24... Nf8! $19 { 0-1 White resigns. } { [%clk 0:09:36] } 0-1


