[Event "GEO-ch"]
[Site "GEO"]
[Date "1963.??.??"]
[White "Nona Gaprindashvili"]
[Black "Alexander Blagidze"]
[Result "1-0"]
[WhiteElo "2064"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B23"]
[Opening "Sicilian Defense: Grand Prix Attack"]
[StudyName "Nona Gaprindashvili"]
[ChapterName "Nona Gaprindashvili - Alexander Blagidze"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/wH2GJgZ8/ucZxfP9B"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/CheckRaiseMate"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 g6 4. Bb5 { An unusual way of playing the Grand Prix. Normally White would start with 4. Nf3, but Nona wants to lure the Black knight to d4 first and then exchange it. } 4... Nd4 5. Bc4 Bg7 6. Nge2 e6 7. Nxd4 cxd4 8. Ne2 Qh4+?! { A bit overzealous. Black should have focused on developing the minor pieces. } (8... b5! 9. Bxb5 Bb7 { With two great bishops exerting pressure on the center, Black is doing very well. } { [%cal Gb7g2] }) 9. Ng3 { The computer doesn't love this, but from a human perspective it makes perfect sense. When your opponent indicates they are interested in making a lot of weird moves to win a pawn, it's often best to give them the pawn and focus on development. } (9. g3 { was also possible. } 9... Qh3 { I assume this was the intention, but it doesn't really work. } (9... Qd8 { Provoking g3 hardly seems worth 2 tempi. }) 10. Ng1 Qg2 11. Qf3 { The queen will be exchanged with little to show for its efforts. }) 9... Qxf4 10. d3 Qc7 (10... Qf6 { Black needed to prevent White from castling. } { [%cal Gf6f1] } 11. Rf1 Qe7 { White has a lead in development, but has lost the right to castle, and Black's position is very solid. }) 11. O-O { Now White's development is flowing very smoothly. } 11... Ne7 12. Bg5 { Taking aim at the weak dark squares. } { [%csl Gf6,Ge7,Gg7] } 12... Nc6 { [%cal Gg3h5] } (12... b5! { The computer really likes this move once again. } 13. Bxb5 Qe5 14. Bxe7 Kxe7 { Having taken control of the dark squares Black is in good shape. }) 13. Nh5! { By placing all his pawns on light squares, Blagidze of course knew he was leaving the dark squares weak, but it's precisely on the light squares where Gaprindashvili lands a series of blows! } 13... gxh5 14. Rxf7! { Another sacrifice on the light squares! } (14. Qxh5? Ne5 { and Black has everything covered. } { [%cal Ge5f7] }) 14... Qe5 { The computer shows that Black could still draw with perfect play, but clearly Blagidze hadn't seen Nona's next move. } (14... h6 15. Bf4 Be5 16. Qxh5 Kd8 17. Qh4+ Ke8 18. Qh5 { neither side has anything better than to repeat. }) 15. Rf5!! { Blagidze resigned because there is no way to stop Qxh5+. } 15... exf5 16. Qxh5+ Kf8 17. Qf7# 1-0


