{ [%evp 0,43,19,31,19,-16,-7,6,-6,6,26,8,23,23,32,32,30,20,17,18,25,28,37,28,27,
29,37,36,32,13,43,29,28,30,33,35,46,26,49,23,37,41,95,87,95,54] }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5 Be6 7. e3 Nbd7 8. Bd3 Bd6 9. O-O c6 10. Bf4 Qc7 11. Qd2 O-O 12. h3 Rfe8 13. Rfc1 (13. Rfe1 { This is what they
usually do. The point is Black's previous move (sort of) threatens Ne4 (see
next move). }) 13... g6 { Just blindly trying to remember my prep without
understanding. It's not a bad move though. } (13... Bxf4 14. exf4 Ne4 15. Nxe4 dxe4 16. Bxe4 Bxh3 { [%cal Ge8e4] } 17. Bxh7+ Kxh7 18. Ng5+ Kg8 19. Nxh3 Rad8 { White's weakened
pawns give Black pretty good compensation for the pawn. }) 14. Rab1 { [%cal Gd3g6,Ge6a2] } 14... Nh5 (14... Bxf4 15. exf4 Ne4 { Now this is just great. } 16. Nxe4 (16. Bxe4 dxe4 17. Ne5) 16... dxe4 17. Bxe4 Bxa2 $19 { [%cal Ga2b1,Ge8e4] }) 15. Bxd6 Qxd6 16. Na4 Ng7 { Looks thematic, but
turns out to be slow and awkward. } (16... Nhf6 17. b4 Ne4 18. Bxe4 dxe4) 17. b4 Re7 (17... Qe7 { The queen is poorly placed on d6. You want a knight there. }) 18. Rb2 Bf5 19. Nc5 Nb6 (19... Bxd3 { Take this trade when you have the chance! } 20. Qxd3 Nb6 { [%cal Rb6c4] }) 20. Be2 Rae8? { Pointless. The rook was
actually better on a8 to prepare a5 in some lines. } 21. a4 Be4 22. Ne1 { Game drawn by agreement Very fortunate that he offered a draw here as I had a
terrible position and was down on time. During the game I felt he was playing
perfectly, but in reality I had chances and just didn't understand how to play
the position. The key idea I missed time and again was ...Ne4! } 1/2-1/2


