1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 Bd6 5. Nbd2 O-O 6. Bd3 c5 7. c3 Bxf4 8. exf4 b6 9. Qe2 a5 (9... Qd6 { This is Christof's recommendation, but I
prefer to keep the d6 square available for a knight. }) 10. O-O Ba6 { Overall a
solid line, but I would prefer to mix it up more against London players. } 11. Bb5? { Doesn't make sense as White's queen will be misplaced on b5 anyway. } 11... Qc7 (11... Bxb5 12. Qxb5 Qc7) 12. Ne5 cxd4 (12... Bxb5 13. Qxb5 Rc8 { The computer likes this, just calmly bringing out the pieces. } { [%cal Rb8c6] }) 13. cxd4 Qc2 14. Bxa6 Nxa6 15. Rab1 Ne4 16. Rfd1 Rfc8 17. a3 Rc7 18. g3 g6 (18... Nxd2 19. Qxd2 Qxd2 20. Rxd2 Rac8 { Black is playing for two
results. I was still dreaming of using my queen actively somehow. } { [%cal Ra6b8,Rf7f6,Rb8c6] }) 19. Qe1 Nxd2 20. Rxd2 Qb3?? (20... Qf5) 21. Ng4 { Completely missed this one. It's
basically over, can't defend the dark squares. } 21... Rc2 22. Qd1 Rac8 23. Ne3 { chika-lily won by resignation Don't be so quick to pass up a chance for a
two-result endgame, these are great EV spots. And be careful about weakening
your king! } 1-0


