1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 { In these variations Black can develop quickly and fight for the center. However, the d6 square can be weak. } 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 (4... Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 (5... Bb4 { Very aggressive, but not very good. } 6. e5 Nd5 7. Bd2 { White has more space and good control of the center. You can use the queen to attack Black's undefended kingside. } { [%cal Gd1g4,Gg4g7] }) 6. Ndb5 { Aiming at the weak d6 square. } { [%csl Gd6][%cal Gb5d6] } 6... Bb4 (6... d6 7. Bf4 { [%cal Gb5d6,Gf4d6,Gd1d6] } 7... e5 8. Bg5 { This transposes to a mainline of the Sveshnikov variation. }) 7. a3 { Trading off this bishop further weakens the dark squares. } (7. Nd6+?! Ke7 8. Nxc8+ Rxc8 { Black's lead in development more than compensate for the king position. }) 7... Bxc3+ 8. Nxc3 d5 9. exd5 exd5 10. Bd3 { Hurrying to castle kingside. } 10... O-O 11. O-O { White should finish developing and start pressuring the isolated d-pawn. } { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gc1g5] }) (4... a6 { The Kan Variation. Black keeps a lot of flexibility on how to develop their pieces. On the other hand, without any pressure on the center, White also has a lot of flexibility. } 5. Bd3!? { Planning to go for a Maroczy Bind setup with c4 after castling, avoiding any annoying Bb4+. } { [%cal Gc2c4] } 5... Nf6 6. O-O Qc7 7. Qe2 { Threatening e5. } { [%cal Ge4e5] } 7... d6 8. c4 { [%cal Gb1c3] }) 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 a6 7. Qf3 { Planning a quick queenside castle. } { [%cal Ge1c1] } *


