[ChapterName "Intro"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/K32PaAoo/64qPrKdz"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/CheckRaiseMate"]
[UTCDate "2021.10.20"]
[UTCTime "22:54:53"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 { The Berlin: the most solid, boring opening out there...
That's what we want our opponent's to think! This repertoire opens with the starting move of the Berlin, 3...Nf6, but follows up with the trickiest, most aggressive lines in every variation. We lull our opponents into a false sense of security, then move in for the kill. } *


[Event "The Bogus Berlin: 4. d3"]
[Date "2021.10.17"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C65"]
[Opening "Ruy Lopez: Berlin Defense, Anti-Berlin Variation, Mortimer Trap"]
[StudyName "The Bogus Berlin"]
[ChapterName "4. d3"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/K32PaAoo/nFgDqWmj"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/CheckRaiseMate"]
[UTCDate "2021.10.17"]
[UTCTime "14:27:00"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Ne7!? { The key move of our line. The knight prepares to swing over to g6, while preparing c6 to kick White's bishop away. But wait a second, what about the e5-pawn??? } 5. Nxe5? { White falls for it! } (5. O-O { The great thing about this trap is even if they don't fall for it, this is a fine line for Black. } 5... Ng6 { Finishing the knight maneuver. } 6. c3 c6 7. Ba4 Be7 { Black has a healthy position. } { [%cal Ge8g8,Gd7d6] }) 5... c6 6. Bc4 Qa5+ { [%cal Ga5e1,Ga5e5] } 7. Nc3 Qxe5 { Black is up a piece with a winning position. The next order of business is to get the pieces out and castle. } { [%cal Ge7g6,Gf8e7,Ge8g8,Gd7d6] } *


[Event "The Bogus Berlin: 4. 0-0"]
[Date "2021.10.17"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C67"]
[Opening "Ruy Lopez: Berlin Defense, Rio Gambit Accepted"]
[StudyName "The Bogus Berlin"]
[ChapterName "4. 0-0"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/K32PaAoo/k56EAkgH"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/CheckRaiseMate"]
[UTCDate "2021.10.17"]
[UTCTime "14:27:34"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 exd4 (5... Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 { would be the famous Berlin Endgame. Not what we're going for! }) 6. Re1 d5 7. Nxd4 Bd6 { Taking aim at the kingside, and getting ready to castle if given the chance. The upside of this approach is it's rare and tricky, and scores well in practice. The downside is White can get a better endgame, but only if they know a long string of only moves. } { [%cal Gd6h2,Gd8h4,Ge8g8] } 8. Nxc6 (8. f3? Qh4 { is an example of how White can go wrong. Black's attack is already winning. } { [%cal Gh4h2] }) 8... Bxh2+! { A spectacular sacrifice! This is the key point of the line, don't forget this move! } 9. Kh1! (9. Kxh2 Qh4+ 10. Kg1 Qxf2+ 11. Kh2 Qh4+ { forces a draw. }) (9. Kf1? Qh4 { is much better for for Black. } { [%cal Gh4f2] }) 9... Qh4 { Black is threatening a deadly discovered check so White has to play very precisely to force a queen trade. } { [%cal Gh2g3,Gh4h1] } 10. Rxe4+! dxe4 11. Qd8+! { This double sacrifice is the only way for White to avoid losing. } 11... Qxd8 12. Nxd8+ Kxd8 13. Kxh2 Be6 { In this endgame material is roughly equal, but White is better because they can use their minor pieces to create threats, whereas Black's extra pawns won't do much in the short term. } { [%cal Gd8e7,Gf7f5] } *


