1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. Nc3 Nd4!? { In keeping with our philosophy, we get in their face with the knight right away. } { [%cal Gd4b5] } 5. Nxe5 (5. Nxd4 exd4 6. Ne2 Nxe4 7. Nxd4 Bc5 { [%cal Gc5f2] } 8. c3 O-O 9. O-O Bxd4 10. cxd4 d5 { Black is better because of White's weak doubled, isolated pawns. } { [%csl Rd4,Rd2] }) (5. Bc4 Bc5 6. Nxe5 Qe7! 7. Nxf7 d5! 8. Nxh8 dxc4 { With active pieces and great control of the center against White's terrible mobilization, Black has fantastic compensation for the exchange. } { [%cal Gc8g4,Ge8c8] }) 5... Qe7! { [%cal Ge7e1] } 6. Nf3 Nxb5 7. Nxb5 Qxe4+ 8. Qe2 Qxe2+ 9. Kxe2 Nd5! { We had to defend c7. } { [%cal Gd5c7] } 10. c4 a6! { Defending with counterattack - we couldn't move the knight because c7 would fall. } 11. cxd5 axb5 { With the open a-file and two bishops, Black stands better. } { [%csl Gf8,Gc8][%cal Ga8a2] } *


