1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 { This is the french tarrasch } 3... c5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. Ngf3 { White plays Nf3 giving up the center pawn but he will most likely get that pawn back } 5... cxd4 6. Bc4 Qd6 7. O-O Nf6 8. Nb3 Nc6 9. Nbxd4 Nxd4 10. Nxd4 Be7 11. c3 O-O 12. Qf3 Qc7 { This move Qc7 attacks the bishop and gains a tempo and this forces the bishop to retreat } 13. Bb3 a5 14. a4 Bd7 { After this position White has more active pieces but he has yet to develop his dark squared bishop and his rook on a1 and black can develop his rooks and I would say that this position is around eaqual } *


